result.execSummary:
Nicholas L. Jack was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means Nicholas L. Jack was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Nicholas L. Jack in court with attorney Jesse Johansen.  Defendant Nicholas L. Jack in custody.  Aaron B Marcoux appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Atty Johansen states defendant will waive extradition.  Court addressed the defendant re: Waiver.  Court finds defendant has freely waived his right to extradition, document tendered to the court - defendant/court signs waiver.

Defendant Nicholas L. Jack in court, in custody.  Aaron B Marcoux appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant wishes to have an attorney.  court public defender's office to to appoint an atty to represent the defendant.  Defendant does not agree he is the person that is wanted from Minnesota - States he is Nicholas Jack he knows nothing about the charges from MN.  Court needs an Identity hearing.  Defendant objects to hearing 2/19/16 requests it be sooner.  Court Clerk is to notify the public defender's office to have an Atty appointed -  Hearing scheduled for January 14, 2016 at 02:45 pm.
